#### What is Scale Factor/N-well Math
- Since we don't draw our layouts in nanometers or whatever the unit length of the components we're working with
- We instead draw everything in units of a basic scale factor often called $\lambda$ 
- It works as conversion ruler between the layout units 
 and the real physical units on the silicon
##### Example
- If a minimum device dimensions are 50 nm
  - Then 1 layout unit = 50 *nm*
   - So 50 *nm* = $0.005 \space \mu m$
   - $0.05 \space \mu m$ = 500 *nm*
 - Then an n-well box drawn 10 by 10 means
    -  Width = 10 layout units 
	- Height = 10 layout units
	   - Each layout unit = 50 nm
- Giving us the actually fabricated size as 
 - 500 *nm* * 500 *nm* = $0.5 \space \mu \cdot 0.5 \mu m$

### DRC 
- For design we set DRC checks 
  - The minimum size (width or length ) of any n-well
- We do this to avoid any unwanted behavior like 
   parasitic transistors or diodes 
